# Decision making in C or conditionals #

We all make some simple decisions like, which clothes to wear to very important decisions like choosing our life partner in our life.

Now, the question is how computers make decisions?

Yes, here comes the importance of decision-making in C.
In C we have different types of decision-making statements.

for example

1. if  statement
2. if else statement
3. Nested if statement
4. if else if
5. switch statements

if statement

syntax:-

if(condition)

{
statement1;
statement2;

}

If the condition in the bracket returns true then the statements in the braces get executed. 
If the condition returns false then the compiler skips the statements written in the braces.

for example-

int A=13,B=10;

if(A>B)
{
  printf("A>B");
  
 }
 printf("Done");
 
In this example, 13 and 10 are assigned to a variable A and B respectively.
 The condition A>B  returns true since 13>10. so the output of the program will be.
 
 Output:- A>B Done.
 
 if else statement

syntax:-

if(condition)

{
ifstatement1;
ifstatement2;

}
else
{
elsestatement1;
elsestatement2;
}


In this type of statement, if the condition inside the bracket returns true then the statements in the braces get executed. 
if the condition returns false then the compiler skips the if statements and execute the else statements. 


Nested if statement

syntax:-

if(condition1)

{
  if(condition2)
  {
    ifstatement1;
    ifstatement2;
   }

}

The name nested if because of an if statement inside another if statement.
Instead, if statements if condition1 satisfies it will check for condition2, and if it also satisfies then the if statements get executed. 

if else if statements

syntax:-

if(condition1)

{
 
    ifstatement1;
    ifstatement2;
 }
 elseif(condition2)
 {
  
    elseifstatement1;
    elseifstatement2;

}
else
{
    elsestatement1;
    elsestatement2;

}

In if else if statement first condition1 in the if statement will check, 
if it is false then it will check condition2 if condition2 returns true then else if statements get executed else the else statements get executed.

switch statements

syntax:-

switch(expression)
{
  case caseconstant1:
                      statements;
                      break;
  case caseconstant2:
                      statements;
                      break;
  default:            
                      statements;
                      break;
}

Now let us explain the switch statement with an example;

int i=10
switch(i)
{
  case 5:
                      printf("In case 5");
                      break;
  case 10:
                      printf("In case 10");
                      break;
  default:            
                      printf("In default");
                      break;
}                 
                      

In this example the value of variable i is initialized as 10. And we are passing the variable i in the switch statement.
The output of the program will be, In case 10 because the case constant 10 matches with the expression inside the switch statement.

